 decline of liberalism, and suburban politics in the wake of the rise of the New Right and the Reagan Revolution in the 1970s and 1980s. Although only a small portion of the population, knowledge professionals in Massachusetts and elsewhere have come to wield tremendous political leverage and power. By probing the possibilities and limitations of these suburban liberals, this rich and nuanced account shows that—far from being an exception to national trends—the suburbs of Massachusetts offer a model for understanding national political realignment and suburban politics in the second half of the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aLiberalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSuburbsxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Conservatism & Liberalism.2bisacsh  a1972 election.  aAmerican politics.  aBoston busing crisis.  aCold War suburbs.  aCold War.  aDemocratic Party.  aEqual Rights Amendment.  aMETCO.  aMassachusetts Miracle.  aMassachusetts exceptionalism.  aMassachusetts liberal.  aMassachusetts.  aMetropolitan Council for Educational Opportunity.  aMichael Dukakis.  aNew Right.  aReagan Revolution.  aRoute 128 suburbs.  aRoute 128.  aThe Battle over the Suburbs.  aVietnam War.  aaffirmative action.  aaffordable housing.  aantiwar movement.  acivil rights.  aclass inequality.  acollective distinctiveness.  adefense spending.  ademographic changes.  aeconomic inequality.  aeconomic problems.  aelectoral politics.  aenvironmental degradation.  aenvironmental inequality.  aenvironmental protection.  aenvironmentalism.  aequal opportunity.  aexclusivity.  afair housing activism.  afair housing movement.  afeminism.  agrassroots activism.  ahigh-tech corridor.  ahigh-tech 